    {
        "content": "<p>Hi everyone!<br>\nI'm quite comfortable with the definition of sheaves on a category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> equipped with a coverage <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span>. I know that, when thinking of sheaves on a topological space <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, these <a href=\"https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/2020/01/07/topos-theory-part-2/\">can be identified with Etále spaces</a>. Now my question is: is there a nice analogue for this construction for sites: given a sheaf <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333em\"/><msup><mi>C</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">p</mi></mrow></msup><mo>→</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F \\colon C^{\\mathsf{op}} \\to Set</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6741em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathsf mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> on a site <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>K</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(C, K)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, can I always write this as a morphism of sites <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>E</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><msub><mi>K</mi><mi>E</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>K</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(E, K_E) \\to (C, K)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>? Something like this must exist, but I don't know what to look up, any help would be greatly appreciated :)</p>",
        "id": 430816315,
        "sender_full_name": "Benjamin Merlin Bumpus (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1712071610
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Riccard Zanfa's <a href=\"https://irinsubria.uninsubria.it/retrieve/e2188be8-1d34-4564-e053-6605fe0a49d6/Tesi%20%283%29.pdf\">PhD thesis</a> deals with this at a very high level. For a more elementary take, you should know that for a presheaf <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span></span>, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{PSh}(\\mathcal{C})/X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">PSh</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is equivalent to the category of presheaves over the category of elements of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, and by pulling back you can deduce that one choice of site for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>K</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Sh}(\\mathcal{C},K)/X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Sh</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is the category of sheaves for a topology on the category of elements of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> derived from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span>. This is made explicit in Caramello's work somewhere (possibly in her \"Denseness conditions...\" paper)</p>",
        "id": 430823450,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1712073564
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My naïve idea for one direction is to just integrate everything in sight: </p>\n<ul>\n<li>modulo suitable size considerations, a coverage <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> on a category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> is just a special kind of presheaf <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333em\"/><msup><mi>C</mi><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msup><mo>→</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K \\colon C^{op} \\to Set</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span></li>\n<li>integrating the sheaf <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span>, we should get the following situation <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>∫</mo><mi>F</mi><mover><mo stretchy=\"true\" minsize=\"3.0em\">→</mo><mpadded width=\"+0.6em\" lspace=\"0.3em\"><msub><mi>π</mi><mi>F</mi></msub></mpadded></mover><msup><mi>C</mi><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msup><mover><mo stretchy=\"true\" minsize=\"3.0em\">→</mo><mpadded width=\"+0.6em\" lspace=\"0.3em\"><mi>K</mi></mpadded></mover><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\int F \\xrightarrow{\\pi_F} C^{op} \\xrightarrow{K} Set</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.2295em;vertical-align:-0.3061em;\"></span><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel x-arrow\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9234em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.322em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight x-arrow-pad\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3448em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.3567em;margin-left:-0.0359em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1433em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"top:-2.689em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"hide-tail\" style=\"height:0.522em;min-width:1.469em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width='400em' height='0.522em' viewBox='0 0 400000 522' preserveAspectRatio='xMaxYMin slice'><path d='M0 241v40h399891c-47.3 35.3-84 78-110 128\n-16.7 32-27.7 63.7-33 95 0 1.3-.2 2.7-.5 4-.3 1.3-.5 2.3-.5 3 0 7.3 6.7 11 20\n 11 8 0 13.2-.8 15.5-2.5 2.3-1.7 4.2-5.5 5.5-11.5 2-13.3 5.7-27 11-41 14.7-44.7\n 39-84.5 73-119.5s73.7-60.2 119-75.5c6-2 9-5.7 9-11s-3-9-9-11c-45.3-15.3-85\n-40.5-119-75.5s-58.3-74.8-73-119.5c-4.7-14-8.3-27.3-11-40-1.3-6.7-3.2-10.8-5.5\n-12.5-2.3-1.7-7.5-2.5-15.5-2.5-14 0-21 3.7-21 11 0 2 2 10.3 6 25 20.7 83.3 67\n 151.7 139 205zm0 0v40h399900v-40z'/></svg></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.011em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1113em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel x-arrow\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.1003em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.322em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight x-arrow-pad\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"top:-2.689em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"hide-tail\" style=\"height:0.522em;min-width:1.469em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width='400em' height='0.522em' viewBox='0 0 400000 522' preserveAspectRatio='xMaxYMin slice'><path d='M0 241v40h399891c-47.3 35.3-84 78-110 128\n-16.7 32-27.7 63.7-33 95 0 1.3-.2 2.7-.5 4-.3 1.3-.5 2.3-.5 3 0 7.3 6.7 11 20\n 11 8 0 13.2-.8 15.5-2.5 2.3-1.7 4.2-5.5 5.5-11.5 2-13.3 5.7-27 11-41 14.7-44.7\n 39-84.5 73-119.5s73.7-60.2 119-75.5c6-2 9-5.7 9-11s-3-9-9-11c-45.3-15.3-85\n-40.5-119-75.5s-58.3-74.8-73-119.5c-4.7-14-8.3-27.3-11-40-1.3-6.7-3.2-10.8-5.5\n-12.5-2.3-1.7-7.5-2.5-15.5-2.5-14 0-21 3.7-21 11 0 2 2 10.3 6 25 20.7 83.3 67\n 151.7 139 205zm0 0v40h399900v-40z'/></svg></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.011em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span></li>\n<li>integrating the composite, you get a thing that looks like <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>∫</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>∘</mo><msub><mi>π</mi><mi>F</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><mo>∫</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\int (K \\circ \\pi_F) \\to \\int F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1111em;vertical-align:-0.3061em;\"></span><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0359em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1111em;vertical-align:-0.3061em;\"></span><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> which my intuition tells me ought to be unaravelable into a presheaf <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>K</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\" lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333em\"/><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>∫</mo><mi>F</mi><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msup><mo>→</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K&#x27; \\colon (\\int F)^{op} \\to Set</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1111em;vertical-align:-0.3061em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7519em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">′</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mclose\"><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> which I'm hoping is actually defining a coverage on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>∫</mo><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\int F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1111em;vertical-align:-0.3061em;\"></span><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span>.... </li>\n</ul>\n<p>Is this at all in the right direction?</p>",
        "id": 430823595,
        "sender_full_name": "Benjamin Merlin Bumpus (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1712073601
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277473\">Morgan Rogers (he/him)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/232160-learning.3A-reading-.26-references/topic/Sheaves.20on.20a.20Site/near/430823450\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Riccard Zanfa's <a href=\"https://irinsubria.uninsubria.it/retrieve/e2188be8-1d34-4564-e053-6605fe0a49d6/Tesi%20%283%29.pdf\">PhD thesis</a> deals with this at a very high level. For a more elementary take, you should know that for a presheaf <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span></span>, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{PSh}(\\mathcal{C})/X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">PSh</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is equivalent to the category of presheaves over the category of elements of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, and by pulling back you can deduce that one choice of site for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>K</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Sh}(\\mathcal{C},K)/X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Sh</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is the category of sheaves for a topology on the category of elements of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> derived from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span>. This is made explicit in Caramello's work somewhere (possibly in her \"Denseness conditions...\" paper)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>oh, thanks Morgan! I'll check this out <span aria-label=\"heart\" class=\"emoji emoji-2764\" role=\"img\" title=\"heart\">:heart:</span></p>",
        "id": 430823710,
        "sender_full_name": "Benjamin Merlin Bumpus (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1712073621
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It sounds like you would have gotten to an idea that worked ;)</p>",
        "id": 430823943,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1712073687
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277473\">Morgan Rogers (he/him)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/232160-learning.3A-reading-.26-references/topic/Sheaves.20on.20a.20Site/near/430823943\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>It sounds like you would have gotten to an idea that worked ;)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>ah damn, I spoiled my own fun <span aria-label=\"rolling on the floor laughing\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f923\" role=\"img\" title=\"rolling on the floor laughing\">:rolling_on_the_floor_laughing:</span></p>",
        "id": 430824188,
        "sender_full_name": "Benjamin Merlin Bumpus (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1712073755
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The thesis you linked looks amazing though, thanks so much! I might get in touch with <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"284376\">@Riccardo Zanfa</span> and <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"284392\">@Olivia Caramello</span> about this stuff <span aria-label=\"heart\" class=\"emoji emoji-2764\" role=\"img\" title=\"heart\">:heart:</span></p>",
        "id": 430824403,
        "sender_full_name": "Benjamin Merlin Bumpus (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1712073825
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Riccardo left academia a few years ago but I can help you get in touch with him if you struggle :)</p>",
        "id": 430828321,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1712075053
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"481356\">Benjamin Merlin Bumpus (he/him)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/232160-learning.3A-reading-.26-references/topic/Sheaves.20on.20a.20Site/near/430816315\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>identified with _Etále_ spaces</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Since we're in the learning stream: the word is <a href=\"https://translate.google.com/details?sl=fr&amp;tl=en&amp;text=Le%20tissu%20a%20%C3%A9t%C3%A9%20%C3%A9tal%C3%A9.&amp;op=translate\">étalé</a>, three syllables, meaning something like \"laid out flat\".</p>\n<p>Let me know if you plan a deep-delve into the resources Morgan pointed out. My PhD thesis has a section giving a nonstandard-analytic treatment of sheaves on topological spaces, relying heavily on étalé spaces. This prompted questions about whether similar concepts could extend to sheaves on a site. I couldn't pursue this line of research at the time, and one of my stumbling blocks was my lack of clarity on how to do étalé spaces without ordinary topology. It might be time to revisit this question.</p>",
        "id": 430841928,
        "sender_full_name": "Zoltan A. Kocsis",
        "timestamp": 1712079680
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Let's not be prescriptive. I prefer the 2-syllable pronunciation \"étale\", which is quite common in English (but not French). See the (surprisingly heated) discussion <a href=\"https://nforum.ncatlab.org/discussion/11283/etale-space/\">here</a>.</p>",
        "id": 430843561,
        "sender_full_name": "Spencer Breiner",
        "timestamp": 1712080286
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think it's okay to accept \"étale\" (and even \"etale\") while rejecting \"etále\", especially considering that \"á\" is not used in French at all as far as I know.</p>",
        "id": 430844229,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1712080530
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Interesting historical note -- evidently, Grothendieck, at least when speaking to a primarily english audience, seems to have pronounced it flatly without multiple syllables \"etale\".  Or at least he did so in the audio recordings Lawvere et al. rescued; <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vmcbm5FxRJE\">Colin McLarty</a> (don't recall timecode sadly)  ... not looking to argue, just a quirky historical tidbit.</p>\n<div class=\"youtube-video message_inline_image\"><a data-id=\"vmcbm5FxRJE\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vmcbm5FxRJE\"><img src=\"https://uploads.zulipusercontent.net/a3a515bf9b67309446e7edf68ec17c4f3e6dea48/68747470733a2f2f692e7974696d672e636f6d2f76692f766d63626d354678524a452f64656661756c742e6a7067\"></a></div>",
        "id": 430847076,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric M Downes",
        "timestamp": 1712081528
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"510824\">Zoltan A. Kocsis</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/232160-learning.3A-reading-.26-references/topic/Sheaves.20on.20a.20Site/near/430841928\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"481356\">Benjamin Merlin Bumpus (he/him)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/232160-learning.3A-reading-.26-references/topic/Sheaves.20on.20a.20Site/near/430816315\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>identified with _Etále_ spaces</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Since we're in the learning stream: the word is <a href=\"https://translate.google.com/details?sl=fr&amp;tl=en&amp;text=Le%20tissu%20a%20%C3%A9t%C3%A9%20%C3%A9tal%C3%A9.&amp;op=translate\">étalé</a>, three syllables, meaning something like \"laid out flat\".</p>\n<p>Let me know if you plan a deep-delve into the resources Morgan pointed out. My PhD thesis has a section giving a nonstandard-analytic treatment of sheaves on topological spaces, relying heavily on étalé spaces. This prompted questions about whether similar concepts could extend to sheaves on a site. I couldn't pursue this line of research at the time, and one of my stumbling blocks was my lack of clarity on how to do étalé spaces without ordinary topology. It might be time to revisit this question.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Ciao bellissimo! Yes, I plan to, I have an application in mind you might like! (also thanks for pointing out the correct spelling: can you tell that I was writing in Portuguese moments before typing my question? <span aria-label=\"rolling on the floor laughing\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f923\" role=\"img\" title=\"rolling on the floor laughing\">:rolling_on_the_floor_laughing:</span> )</p>",
        "id": 430852341,
        "sender_full_name": "Benjamin Merlin Bumpus (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1712083499
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Just a note on the naming thing: I believe the adjective \"étale\" is the word that we want to use when talking about topologies (as in \"mer étale\", a completly flat sea). The adjective étalé is a different word with a similar meaning:<br>\nÉtale = slack<br>\nÉtalé = spread</p>",
        "id": 430980905,
        "sender_full_name": "Rémy Tuyéras",
        "timestamp": 1712143963
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Correct, the étalé of \"<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sheaf_(mathematics)#Etale_space\">étalé space</a>\" and the étale of \"<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89tale_cohomology\">étale cohomology</a>\" are unrelated.</p>",
        "id": 431005216,
        "sender_full_name": "Zoltan A. Kocsis",
        "timestamp": 1712151404
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I decided to act like an American and just write \"etale\": in this case, the math is hard enough without worrying about accents.</p>",
        "id": 431148786,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1712167741
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I always wondered why these terms weren't translated to English...? Slack and spread seem fine to me</p>",
        "id": 431237780,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1712214271
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In the case of étalé space there's a perfectly good English term \"local homeomorphism\".</p>",
        "id": 431318954,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1712238843
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X\\to B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> is a vector bundle or fibration of some sort, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is usually called the \"total space\".  I wonder why this terminology is not applied to local homeomorphisms...  I mean, it still makes sense to me (when you apply the Grothendieck construction to a (pre)sheaf <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span>, people call <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>∫</mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\int\\!F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1111em;vertical-align:-0.3061em;\"></span><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> the \"total category\" if I'm not mistaken).</p>",
        "id": 431327890,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Mazza",
        "timestamp": 1712241306
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, etale spaces don't look like your typical \"total space\" - they look like a stack of filo, so we can do very special things with them.   So it makes some sense to give them a special name, even though they <em>are</em> total spaces.</p>",
        "id": 431369438,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1712252421
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But \"local homeomorphism\" is precise and clear.</p>",
        "id": 431383570,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1712257325
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Of course it sounds like it is talking about the map rather than the total space, but you can't talk about the map without talking about its domain, and really when you say \"étalé space\" you're referring to the space <em>together with the map</em>, since a space can't be \"étalé\" unless you specify what it's étalé over and how.  So I don't really see this as an objection.</p>",
        "id": 431383814,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1712257411
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/232160-learning.3A-reading-.26-references/topic/Sheaves.20on.20a.20Site/near/431318954\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>In the case of étalé space there's a perfectly good English term \"local homeomorphism\".</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Ah, right! I actually like that, but it's so long I end up using étale again <span aria-label=\"big smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f604\" role=\"img\" title=\"big smile\">:big_smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 431458457,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1712300385
    }
]